# {{.Type}}: {{.Name}}

~> **Note:** Ephemeral resources are available in Terraform v1.10 and later.

`{{.Name}}` generates a short-lived access token (JWT) for a MongoDB Atlas [Service Account](https://www.mongodb.com/docs/atlas/api/service-accounts-overview/) using the OAuth 2.0 Client Credentials flow.

The access token is generated during each Terraform operation and is never persisted to state or plan. For more information on where to use ephemeral values, see [Ephemeral values](https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/manage-sensitive-data/ephemeral).

-> **NOTE:** The access token is valid for 3600 seconds (1 hour) and cannot be refreshed. Set `revoke_on_closure = true` to revoke the token as soon as the Terraform operation ends.

## Example Usages

### Basic usage (provider credentials)

If your provider is already configured with Service Account credentials (`client_id` and `client_secret`), the ephemeral resource uses those credentials by default.

```terraform
ephemeral "mongodbatlas_service_account_jwt" "token" {}

# Use the token in a provider block.
provider "mongodbatlas" {
  alias        = "ephemeral"
  access_token = ephemeral.mongodbatlas_service_account_jwt.token.access_token
}
```

### Explicit credentials

Pass `client_id` and `client_secret` directly to generate a token for a specific Service Account.

```terraform
ephemeral "mongodbatlas_service_account_jwt" "token" {
  client_id     = var.atlas_sa_client_id
  client_secret = var.atlas_sa_client_secret
}
```

For complete end-to-end examples, see the [`examples/mongodbatlas_service_account_jwt/`](https://github.com/mongodb/terraform-provider-mongodbatlas/tree/v2.9.0/examples/mongodbatlas_service_account_jwt) directory.

## Credential Resolution

If `client_id` and `client_secret` are set on the `ephemeral` block, those values are used. Otherwise, the resource falls back to the Service Account credentials configured on the provider.

This resource requires Service Account credentials. Programmatic Access Keys (PAKs) cannot be used to generate a JWT.

{{ .SchemaMarkdown | trimspace }}

## Rate Limits

Atlas enforces rate limits on Service Account token generation: 10 JWTs per minute and 100 active JWTs per Service Account. Unless `revoke_on_closure` is enabled, tokens remain active until they expire (3600 seconds).


For more information, see [Service Accounts Overview](https://www.mongodb.com/docs/atlas/api/service-accounts-overview/) in the MongoDB Atlas documentation.

